  <main class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-5 py-12 sm:py-14">
    <p class="text-[12px] tracking-[0.22em] uppercase text-ink/70">
      A short illustration
    </p>

    <h1 class="mt-4 font-serif font-light tracking-tight text-[36px] sm:text-[44px] leading-[1.08]">
      From Product to Reference
    </h1>

    <p class="mt-5 font-body text-[16px] leading-[1.75] text-ink/85">
      Most companies treat growth as a visibility problem. More reach. More messaging. More acceleration.
      I’ve learned that the real challenge appears earlier, and quieter: becoming understood before becoming big.
    </p>

    <div class="mt-8 rounded-2xl border border-ink/15 bg-base/60 p-6 shadow-soft">
      <p class="font-body text-[14px] leading-[1.8] text-ink/85">
        This page outlines how I think about the shift from “one option among many” to “the default people name.”
        It’s meant to be legible, not copyable. The actual work is always company-specific.
      </p>
    </div>

    <section class="mt-10 space-y-10">
      <div>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-[20px] leading-[1.25]">1. Growth doesn’t fail because of competition</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 font-body text-[15px] leading-[1.85] text-ink/85">
          It fails because of confusion. When a company scales faster than it is understood, misunderstandings multiply:
          internally, externally, structurally. Most growth efforts amplify that confusion instead of resolving it.
          My work usually starts here — before growth becomes visible.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-[20px] leading-[1.25]">2. Reference brands don’t win attention — they win language</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 font-body text-[15px] leading-[1.85] text-ink/85">
          Some brands stop being a choice and become the placeholder people use for the category itself.
          Once that happens, comparison changes: alternatives are no longer equal options — they are deviations.
          This is not branding. It’s a shift in how decisions are made.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-[20px] leading-[1.25]">3. Categories are not given — they are framed</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 font-body text-[15px] leading-[1.85] text-ink/85">
          Especially in technology, categories are unstable. What something <em>is</em> matters more than what it <em>does</em>.
          Whoever defines that meaning controls how the product is evaluated. Many companies explain features while the category stays unclear.
          That gap is where growth becomes fragile.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-[20px] leading-[1.25]">4. In the AI age, the biggest risk is underestimation</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 font-body text-[15px] leading-[1.85] text-ink/85">
          The most serious failures are rarely spectacular. They are moments where systems keep operating, humans lose visibility,
          and responsibility becomes diffuse. That is not a technical problem alone. It is a problem of understanding.
          Growth without understanding scales risk quietly.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-[20px] leading-[1.25]">5. Becoming a reference requires restraint</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 font-body text-[15px] leading-[1.85] text-ink/85">
          The companies that become defaults don’t talk more. They talk less, but with precision.
          They decide what not to explain. They don’t chase relevance; they create conditions where relevance follows.
          This kind of growth cannot be rushed. And it cannot be templated.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-[20px] leading-[1.25]">6. How I work</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 font-body text-[15px] leading-[1.85] text-ink/85">
          I work with companies that want to define their category, grow without being misunderstood, and remain steerable as complexity increases.
          I don’t apply pre-built models. Every roadmap depends on the company, the moment, and the risk it carries.
          That work doesn’t belong on a public page.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-12 rounded-2xl border border-ink/15 bg-base/60 p-7 shadow-soft">
      <h3 class="font-serif text-[18px] leading-[1.25]">If this resonates</h3>
      <p class="mt-3 font-body text-[15px] leading-[1.8] text-ink/85">
        If you’re responsible for growth in a complex environment and want to keep it steerable, I’m open to a conversation.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-6 flex flex-wrap gap-3 items-center">
